Phase 2 — Internalize sample playback
Currently the effect is a 1-in/1-out AudioStream node fed by AudioPlayMemory. For time-stretching, the effect must own the read pointer into the sample buffer so it can advance it at a variable rate.

2.1 Change to a 0-input, 1-output audio object

Remove receiveReadOnly(). Change the AudioStream constructor to declare 0 inputs:


AudioEffectPhaseVocoder() : AudioStream(0, nullptr), ...
2.2 Add sample buffer API


void setSample(const int16_t *data, uint32_t numSamples);
void play();
void stop();
void setLoop(bool loop);
bool isPlaying();
Store the pointer, length, and a float read_pos (fractional read position).

2.3 Replace blocklist with direct reads from the sample buffer

Instead of collecting audio_block_t blocks from the audio graph, read directly from the sample buffer into FFT_Frame when processing. Use linear interpolation on fractional read positions:


float s0 = sample_data[(int)read_pos];
float s1 = sample_data[(int)read_pos + 1];
float frac = read_pos - (int)read_pos;
FFT_Frame[i] = s0 + frac * (s1 - s0);
Advance read_pos by analysis_hop per frame (Phase 3 will make this variable).

2.4 Remove the 8-block state machine

The blocklist/state machine was necessary because audio arrived one block at a time from the stream. Now that we own the buffer, we can fill FFT_Frame in one shot every update. The sliding window becomes a simple read_pos advance.

Phase 3 — Implement time-stretching
3.1 Add stretch factor control


void setStretch(float factor);  // 0.5 = half duration, 2.0 = double duration
Store as float stretch_factor. Compute:


float analysis_hop = AUDIO_BLOCK_SAMPLES / stretch_factor;  // can be fractional
3.2 Update the phase analysis formula

The true instantaneous frequency of bin k is:


expected_delta = 2π × k × analysis_hop / FFT_SIZE
deviation      = (phase[k] - last_phase[k] - expected_delta)  [wrapped to -π..π]
true_omega[k]  = 2π × k / FFT_SIZE  +  deviation / analysis_hop
true_omega[k] is in radians/sample and is independent of hop size — it is the actual frequency present in the signal.

3.3 Accumulate phase at synthesis rate


Phase_Sum[k] += true_omega[k] × AUDIO_BLOCK_SAMPLES
Using fixed AUDIO_BLOCK_SAMPLES (128) as the synthesis hop keeps the output locked to Teensy's block clock regardless of stretch.

3.4 Advance read position by analysis_hop each frame


read_pos += analysis_hop;
if (read_pos >= sample_length) {
    if (looping) read_pos = fmodf(read_pos, sample_length);
    else { playing = false; return; }
}
Because analysis_hop can be fractional, wrap with fmodf not integer arithmetic.

Phase 4 — Quality improvements for drum beats
4.1 Increase FFT overlap for better transient resolution

Drums have sharp transients. OVER_SAMPLE=8 (hop=128) is reasonable but the current code only processes one FFT per update(). Confirm this is truly sliding every 128 samples — if not, increase overlap.

4.2 Phase-locked vocoder for transients (optional, significant improvement)

Standard phase vocoders smear transients ("phasiness"). The fix: detect transient frames (large energy increase between frames) and reset Phase_Sum to the analysis phase instead of accumulating. This is the single biggest quality improvement for drum material.

Detection:


float energy = /* sum of Synth_Magn[k] */;
if (energy > prev_energy * transient_threshold) {
    // reset: Phase_Sum[k] = analysis_phase[k]
}
4.3 Anti-aliasing for fast compression (stretch < 1)

When analysis_hop > AUDIO_BLOCK_SAMPLES (compression), you're skipping samples. Apply a simple low-pass (or use the FFT magnitude rolloff naturally) to avoid aliasing.

